6:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both Drift and RabbitX use 1-hour funding intervals with TWAP-based rate calculations. Drift's vAMM hybrid model creates funding rates through its virtual liquidity mechanism, while RabbitX relies on off-chain orderbook matching with Starknet settlement. Drift's JIT auctions can create temporary rate distortions during volatile periods. RabbitX's smaller liquidity pools may result in more extreme funding rate swings compared to Drift's deeper markets."}]]}]
7:["$","$Lb",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better funding rate arbitrage opportunities?","answer":"Drift typically offers more stable arbitrage opportunities due to higher liquidity and trading volume. RabbitX may have more extreme rate swings but with limited position sizes due to smaller market depth."},{"question":"How do settlement risks compare between Drift and RabbitX?","answer":"Drift faces Solana network congestion risks that can affect settlement timing. RabbitX uses Starknet L2 for settlement but has smart contract risks as an early-stage protocol with less battle-tested infrastructure."},{"question":"Which platform has lower total trading costs for arbitrage?","answer":"Both have identical fee structures at 0.02%/0.05%, but RabbitX offers zero gas fees while Drift requires Solana transaction fees. However, Drift's deeper liquidity often provides better execution prices that offset gas costs."},{"question":"How do liquidation mechanics affect funding rate positions?","answer":"Drift uses a complex multi-tier liquidation system that can create cascading effects during volatile periods. RabbitX has simpler cross-margin liquidations but limited insurance fund backing compared to Drift's established protection mechanisms."}]}]
